<section class="prose">
  <h1>Kinder to the planet.<br />By about thirty times.</h1>
  <p class="updated">Measured, not vibes. Working shown below.</p>

  <p>
    Right now, the whole of Eleven — every space, every service, every
    helper — draws less electricity than a nightlight. That's not because
    it's small (though it is, for now). It's because of how it's built, and
    the advantage holds as it grows.
  </p>

  <ul class="stats" aria-label="Headline carbon figures">
    <li>
      <span class="stat-n">~2 g</span>
      <span class="stat-l">CO&#8322;e per member per year, at scale</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="stat-n">~75 g</span>
      <span class="stat-l">the same figure for a conventional app stack</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="stat-n">~30&times;</span>
      <span class="stat-l">the difference (estimates range 10&ndash;50&times;)</span>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="stat-n">0.5 J</span>
      <span class="stat-l">of server energy per message, versus 20&ndash;30 joules conventionally</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why it's so much lighter</h2>
  <p>
    No single trick — four ordinary decisions that multiply:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>It sleeps when you do.</strong> Most services keep every
      customer's machinery running around the clock, sized for the busiest
      moment ever expected. Each Eleven space simply goes to sleep when
      nobody's chatting — costing nothing — and wakes in a blink when
      someone speaks. Group chats are quiet most of the day; ours spend
      that time off.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Small programs.</strong> An entire Eleven space — the app, its
      database, everything — is one file that runs in about as much memory
      as a handful of browser tabs. The industry standard for the same job
      is measured in the hundreds of times more.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Privacy saves power.</strong> Because everything is encrypted
      before it reaches us, our servers <em>can't</em> analyse, index, mine,
      or &ldquo;enrich&rdquo; your conversations. Every feature a server
      can't see is a feature it can't burn watts computing. Surveillance
      isn't just rude — it's expensive.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Tiny apps.</strong> The iPhone app is smaller than a single
      photo. Millions of people downloading hundred-megabyte updates every
      fortnight is a real, ongoing energy cost — one we've designed away.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What about the AI?</h2>
  <p>
    Eleven is <a href="/story/">built with AI</a>, and AI has a real energy
    cost — we won't pretend otherwise. Our answer is the factory principle:
    spend the factory's energy once, on making software that then sips
    power for its whole life. What we refuse to do is both at once — burn
    energy building software <em>and</em> burn it forever running bloated
    results. The optional AI helpers inside Eleven are exactly that,
    optional, and spaces that don't use them don't spend a joule on them.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bits</h2>
  <p>
    These are careful estimates with error bars, not gospel:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      The absolute numbers could be off by 2&ndash;3&times; either way; the
      <em>ratio</em> is sturdier, because most uncertainties hit both sides
      equally and cancel.
    </li>
    <li>
      Sleeping-when-idle is most of the trick. If every space chatted
      around the clock, the advantage would shrink to &ldquo;only&rdquo;
      5&ndash;10&times; — the part that comes from small, efficient
      programs.
    </li>
    <li>
      Where the electricity comes from matters enormously, for us and for
      everyone else. Cleaner grids shrink everyone's numbers; ours stays
      the smaller one.
    </li>
    <li>
      The comparison gives the conventional stack the benefit of the doubt
      — a plain chat service, no analytics or data pipelines. Against a
      real surveillance-funded messenger, the gap widens.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The method, briefly</h2>
  <p>
    The Eleven side starts from live measurements of our production fleet —
    real memory, real load, on real hardware — projected to a million
    spaces using the
    <a href="https://www.cloudcarbonfootprint.org/docs/methodology/">Cloud
    Carbon Footprint</a> methodology's published coefficients. The
    conventional side is calibrated against the best public data on
    well-run and typical fleets. The architecture that makes the numbers
    possible has <a href="/planet-scale/">a page of its own</a>, and the
    rest of the technical detail lives on
    <a href="/nerds/">the nerdy stuff</a>.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    ~2 g versus ~75 g of CO&#8322;e per member per year: the difference
    between an infrastructure that sleeps when its members do, and one that
    idles at peak provisioning forever.
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The thinking behind building software this way has its own manifesto:
    <a href="https://11factor.org">The Eleven Factors</a>.
  </p>
</section>
